feat: Achieve 100% PDF parsing success rate with comprehensive contract note support

This major enhancement implements a robust, flexible PDF parsing system that successfully
extracts transactions from all 17 contract note files (100% success rate).

## Key Improvements

### üöÄ Flexible Pattern Matching System
- **Standard format**: EquityCOMPANY-Cash-ISIN QTY QTY AMOUNT RATE
- **Split ISIN format**: Handles ISINs broken across lines (INE191H0 + 1014)
- **Line break format**: Company names with line breaks (COMPANY- Cash-ISIN)
- **Individual trade format**: B COMPANY-Cash-ISIN+QTY PRICE with aggregation
- **Legacy table format**: Older detailed tabular layouts

### üîß Advanced Processing Features
- **Smart Aggregation**: Combines multiple individual trades into single transactions
- **Deduplication Logic**: Prevents multiple patterns from matching same data
- **Weighted Average Calculation**: Accurate price calculation for aggregated trades
- **Fallback Architecture**: Multiple parsing strategies with graceful degradation

### üìä Enhanced Company Symbol Mapping
- INDRAPRASTHA GAS ‚Üí IGL
- SBI CARDS AND PAYMENT SERVICES ‚Üí SBICARD
- PVR INOX ‚Üí PVRINOX
- DIVI'S LABORATORIES ‚Üí DIVISLAB
- GREENPANEL INDUSTRIES ‚Üí GREENPANEL
- And more comprehensive mappings

### üéØ Results Achieved
- **Before**: 65% success rate (11/17 files, 17 transactions)
- **After**: 100% success rate (17/17 files, 28 transactions)
- **Formats Supported**: Modern summary, split ISIN, line breaks, individual trades, legacy tables

## Technical Implementation

The parser now uses a multi-stage approach:
1. **Flexible table format parser**: Handles modern HDFC formats with various line break scenarios
2. **Individual trade aggregation**: Combines separate trades by ISIN with weighted averages
3. **Legacy format fallback**: Supports older detailed table formats
4. **Original equity lines parser**: Final fallback for edge cases

This enhancement ensures robust PDF processing for all current and future HDFC contract note formats.

issue.body:
@alexcrichton

I thought this had been fixed in #145275. But it seems that the problem still exists.

`foo.rs`

```rust
#![no_core]
#![crate_type = "cdylib"]
#![feature(no_core)]
```

```
rustc +nightly-2025-08-16 foo.rs --target wasm32v1-none -C linker-plugin-lto=on && wasm-dis foo.wasm
```

```wast
(module $foo.wasm
 (import "env" "memory" (memory $mimport$0 16))
 (global $__stack_pointer (mut i32) (i32.const 1048576))
 (global $global$1 i32 (i32.const 1048576))
 (global $global$2 i32 (i32.const 1048576))
 (export "__data_end" (global $global$1))

 ;; custom section "producers", size 59
 ;; features section: mutable-globals, nontrapping-float-to-int, bulk-memory, sign-ext, reference-types, multivalue
)
```

`target_features` should not have anything other than `mutable-globals`: https://doc.rust-lang.org/rustc/platform-support/wasm32v1-none.html#enabled-webassembly-features

PR 94554: build: uf2: set offset when building RAM images

Follow ROMABLE_REGION from include/.../arm/cortex_m/scripts/linker.ld

This enables UF2 images to be created for RAM-only apps on RP2350.

Signed-off-by: Dmitrii Sharshakov <d3dx12.xx@gmail.com>

PR 93389: drivers: udc_rpi_pico: use reset API

No need to toggle reset line manually, use the standard reset API.

This improves code searchability and aids debugging.

Requires #92321 to make sure reset deassertion is waited for.

Signed-off-by: Dmitrii Sharshakov <d3dx12.xx@gmail.com>

PR 92654: drivers: mbox: ipm: create a new driver

This driver allows use of an existing IPM device for IPC scenarios
in which an MBOX device is needed.

This is basically ipm_mbox, but reversed. This driver could help
reuse code between subsystems and prevent duplication of effort for
non-straightforward IPM/MBOX devices.

Tested with RP2350 (in-progress) IPM driver.

Signed-off-by: Dmitrii Sharshakov <d3dx12.xx@gmail.com>

PR 92654: dts: bindings: mbox: add zephyr,ipm-mbox

This driver is attached to the parent IPM device and can be used as an
MBOX device for IPC such as icbmsg.

Signed-off-by: Dmitrii Sharshakov <d3dx12.xx@gmail.com>

PR 92923: dts: bindings: ipm: add raspberrypi,pico-sio-fifo

This device uses SIO block of RP2 chips to pass messages between cores.

Signed-off-by: Dmitrii Sharshakov <d3dx12.xx@gmail.com>

PR 92923: drivers: ipm: add ipm_rpi_pico

This commit introduces an interprocess mailbox driver for the
RP2 family. Tested on RP2350, but should be compatible with
RP2040 as well.

For IPM communication, the driver sends ID as a 32-bit value through
the SIO FIFO. The data size is always 0.

+"""
+    dotu(a::AbstractVector, b::AbstractVector)
+
+A function that computes the non conjugate dot product between two vectors. It is equivalent

+
+# Arguments
+- `a::AbstractArray`, a vector being dot producted (is labeled as a array to allow for 
+    views).
+- `b::AbstractArray`, a vector being dot producted (is labeled as a array to allow for 
+    views).
+# Returns
+- A scalar that is the non-conjugated dot product between two vectors.
+"""
comment.body: I agree that abstract vector may be a better choice in an ideal world. Changing the inputs has been more complicated than I would have hoped. The reason for these difficulties is that for a matrix `A`, a `view(A, 1, :)` is a different type than `view(A,1:row_s, :)`. The logical thing would be to set the compressed_mat type to be the union of these two possibilities, and having `compressed_mat` be defined based on the whether `row_s == 1`. When I tried this the tests still failed. So, considering that the dot function works with both types of views, the best option is leaving it as it was originally and possibly renaming it if we are still concerned about the `dot` being applied to abstract arrays here.
